reason.tex:
%text \textbf{Taking stock of the facts}
The insurance company has insured a total of \[ 2000 + 4000 + 6000 = 12,000 \] persons.
And therefore, % \begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|} \hline & \text{Meaning} & \text{Probability} \\ \hline P(S) & \text{Rides a scooter} & \frac{2000}{12000} = \frac{1}{6} \\ \hline P(C) & \text{Drives a car} & \frac{4000}{12000} = \frac{1}{3} \\ \hline P(T) & \text{Drives a truck} & \frac{6000}{12000} = \frac{1}{2} \\ \hline \end{tabular}of %text
We have also been told the probabilities of having an accident \underline\text{given} the vehicle type.
Expressed mathematically, % \begin{align} P(A\vert S) &= 0.01 \\ P(A\vert C) &= 0.03 \\ P(A\vert T) &= 0.15 \end{align}

options.tex:
\begin{align}
P(S\vert A) &= \dfrac{P(A\vert S)\cdot P(S)}
{P(A\vert S)\cdot P(S) + P(A\vert C)\cdot P(C) + P(A\vert T)\cdot P(T)}\\
&= \dfrac{0.01\times\frac{1}{6}}
{0.01\times \frac{1}{6} + 0.03\times\frac{1}{3} + 0.15\times\frac{1}{2}} = \frac{1}{52}
\end{align}

reason.tex:
%text
We know from Bayes' Theorem that 

%

\begin{align}
P(S\vert A)\cdot P(A) &= P(A\vert S)\cdot P(S) \\ 
\therefore P(S\vert A) &= \dfrac{P(A\vert S)\cdot P(S)}{P(A)} \\ 
\text{But }P(A) &= P(A \vert S)\cdot P(S) + \ldots + P(A\vert T)\cdot P(T) \\
&= 0.01\times\frac{1}{6} + 0.03\times\frac{1}{3} + 0.15\times\frac{1}{2}\\
\text{So }P(S\vert A) &= \dfrac{0.01\times \frac{1}{3}}
{0.01\times\frac{1}{6} + 0.03\times\frac{1}{3} + 0.15\times\frac{1}{2}} \\
&= \frac{1}{52}
\end{align}
